pageComponents.content:
The architecture of this application is made of several components

  1. A Raspberry Pi is running in the home with a Boomi Atom behind the firewall

    1. It uses the RxTx JNI library to pull electric utility meter consumption data via a serial port. The connected device is a Rainforest Automation Raven USB device.
    2. The solar production data is received via an http request to the portal page for the Enphase Envoy device on a local IP address. This device is what controls the solar all the panels in the solar array. Since there is a problem with Enphase's current production API, instead the home page is "scraped" to get the current production value
    3. The process runs on schedule every 5 minutes pushing data to a MySQL database in the cloud
  2. A Flow service is implemented in the Atom Cloud to pull data out of MySQL to drive the Flow UI

Alerts are posted to the #go-solar-alerts slack channel. These alerts warn when on peak consumption is excessive. (Note the threshold is set very low in order to demonstrate alerts)

 

Email alerts - NOT YET IMPLEMENTED

These charts compare solar production vs total consumption. The parabolic shape of solar production corresponds to the sun's movement during the day. The Time of Use data shows the relative pricing of consumed electricity at the corresponding time of day.

pageComponents.content:
Welcome to the Go Solar! application. This application monitors the performance of an actual solar/photovoltaic system located on the roof of a residence in Poway, California.

A solar panel converts the energy from the sun into electric power measured in "Watts (W)". If more electricity is produced by the solar panels than is in use by the home, that energy will be fed back to the electric grid where it will be purchased by the electric company, San Diego Gas and Electric (SDG&E). If the home is consuming more electricity than can be produced by the solar array, then energy will be drawn from the electric grid and the owner will be billed for that usage.

Energy is measured in "Watt Hours (wH)". For example if you run a 100 watt light bulb for 2 hours. That will consume 2 X 100 = 200 wH of energy. Kilo-Watt-Hours (1000 wH) is what appears on your electric bill.

Most utility companies charge a fixed rate for electricity used (wH). SDG&E is implementing a new "Time of Use" billing system that will charge different rates for different times of day.
The goal of a homeowner is to minimize electricity consumption during the high-cost peak time periods.
